{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd8494c6-0a0c-49e7-9952-9b1163afe17b","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events API** in your `MauiProgram.cs` (or anywhere you configure the app builder):\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnPause\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnStop\n        }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code isolated.\n- The delegates receive the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call native APIs directly.\n- Other events like `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc. are available via the same fluent API.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc74e20b-00bd-4446-b9cc-f2961c2789aa","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":365},"id":"dcde48a2-1fa6-4bbb-84bd-f2f03abcd7ba","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:43:58.198Z","parentId":"a33c8e95-9c6c-475b-afc2-8147b071b634"}
